"The sea is ours": Bolivia, which has no exit to the sea, hopes that the court will grant it a way out of the Pacific Ocean
Sailors patrol a naval center full of cranes in La Paz.
There's an ocean-colored flag on public buildings.
Sea bases from Lake Titicaca to Amazon are plowing the wing: “We have a right to the sea.
It's our duty to return it."
In all of Bolivia, which has no access to the sea, the memory of the lost seashore for Chile's sake during the conflicts due to resources in the 19th century is still alive – just as the longing for the re-sea voyages of the Pacific Ocean.
While Bolivia awaits a verdict by the International Court of Justice, expected on October 1st, after a five-year process, hopes may be at the highest level in decades.
"Bolivia has momentum, the spirit of unity and peace and, of course, optimisticly awaits the outcome," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians across the country will look at the International Court of Justice's verdict on large screens and hope that the Hague court will decide in favour of Bolivia's view that after decades of demanding negotiations, Chile is obliged to negotiate the surrender of a sovereign exit to Bolivia.
Here comes Morales, the Bolivian charismatic indigenous president facing a controversial battle to be re-elected next year, can also benefit from Monday's verdict.
"We are close to returning the Pacific," he promised at the end of August.
But some analysts believe it is unlikely that the court will rule in Bolivia's favour and that little would change if so.
The Dutch-based UN body has no authority to allocate Chilean territory and has said it will not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
That the International Court of Justice ruling comes only six months after the final hearings, means the case "was not complex," said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
Instead of promoting Bolivia's interests, the last four years may have set them back.
"The question of access to the sea has taken over the current Bolivian leadership," Zárate said.
Morales' belligerent rhetoric buried every good will of Chile, he believes.
Bolivia and Chile will continue dialogue at some point, but after this it will be extremely difficult to negotiate.
Those two countries haven't exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivian representative in The Hague, disagrees with the view that the court has made an unusual decision quickly.
Monday will bring Bolivia "an unusual opportunity to start a new era in relations with Chile" and the opportunity to "stop 139 years of disagreement with mutual benefit", he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales – still one of Latin America's favorite presidents – used the maritime issue as a political crutch.
"Bolivia will never give up the right to access the Pacific," he added.
"The verdict is an opportunity to see that we need to overcome the past."
