John Edward: Language skills that citizens of the world need
Scottish independent schools have a tradition of academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with another package of outstanding exam results, and additional weight is given by individual and joint successes in sports, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, this school represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) is trying to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further education and higher education, the career they want and make them citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement the above-mentioned school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be the favorite and desired subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak to a man who understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in your mother tongue, it goes into his heart."
This statement is a powerful reminder that we cannot use only English if we want to build trust and relations with people from other countries.
The latest results of the final exams this year show that the highest grades in languages were obtained by independent school students.
A total of 68% of foreign students received excellent grades.
The data collected in 74 SCIS schools show that 72% of students received an excellent grade for Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French-learning students and 63% of Spanish-learning students also received the highest possible score.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a key skill that children and youth will surely need in the future.
Today languages as elective objects are considered as important as STEM items (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools, as in other places.
A survey conducted by the United Kingdom Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 revealed that 17% of employers cannot fill jobs due to lack of labour with language skills.
Thus, language skills are becoming increasingly imperative for preparing young people for careers.
As more and more jobs demand language knowledge, these skills are key in the globalized world.
Regardless of career choice, people who have learned to speak a foreign language in the future will feel the benefits of such long - term skills.
A person who speaks multiple languages can communicate directly with strangers, and that gives them priority over competition.
According to a survey by YouGov in 2013 involving more than 4,000 adults, 75% of respondents in the United Kingdom do not know a foreign language well enough to communicate on it, and French is the only language that speaks the bidigital percentage of respondents, more specifically 15%.
Therefore, investing in language learning is very important for children today.
If children learn more languages, especially languages from developing countries, they will have more opportunities to find good employment.
In Scotland, every school offers a variety of languages.
Some schools will include classical, modern languages in their program, while others will opt for languages considered to be the most important in the United Kingdom of 2020, for example Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests, independent schools will always have a variety of choices, as well as teaching staff who are expert in this area.
Scottish independent schools provide children with an environment in which they will prepare and arm the skills needed for success, regardless of what the future has in store for us.
One cannot ignore the fact that today’s global business is very important for the future of each country, so it must also affect education.
Therefore, knowledge of modern languages should really be viewed as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer language selection, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Council of Scottish Independent Schools
