North Korea announces that "no way" for unilateral disarmament without trust
On Saturday, the North Korean Foreign Minister told the United Nations that further sanctions increase distrust of the United States and there is no way that North Korea will unilaterally disarm and give up nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho said at the UN General Assembly that North Korea took "significant measures of goodwill" last year, for example halted nuclear and missile tests, dismantled the nuclear testing station and decided to halt nuclear technology and weapons development.
"But we did not get a satisfactory reaction from the United States," he added.
"If we do not trust the United States, we do not have faith in our national security. Under such circumstances there is no way we will disarm ourselves first unilaterally."
While Ri reiterated the well-known North Korean complaints against Washington's resistance to a "professional" approach to denuclearisation under which North Korea would gradually be abolished, its statement is significant because it did not reject unilateral denuclearisation as Pyongyang did in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first meeting in the history of the current US President and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12th, when Kim made a promise to work on the "denuklearization of the Korean Peninsula", while Trump assured the security of North Korea.
North Korea wants to officially end the Korean war that lasted from 1950 to 1953, but the United States has conditioned Pyongyang to give up nuclear weapons before then.
Washington also ignored calls for a reduction in strict international sanctions for North Korea.
"The U.S. insists that denuclearisation be done before then and increases pressure by sanctioning its objective and even opposes "the declaration of the end of the war", Ri added.
"Perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is only a delusion of people who know nothing about us.
The main problem is that continued sanctions increase distrust."
Ri did not mention whether there were plans for Kim and Trump's second meeting that the President of the United States spoke of earlier this week in the United Nations.
But the minister noted that Kim and South Korea's leader Moon Jae-in held as many as three meetings in the last five months and added, "If the denuclearization had been sought by South Korea, not by the US, the denuclearisation of the Korean peninsula would not have led to such a halt."
Regardless, the tone of Minister Rio's speech differed greatly from last year when he spoke before the UN General Assembly and said that targeting the continental United States with missiles was inevitable after evil President Trump called Kim a "man rocket" on a suicide mission.
Last year, Trump, who threatened to "complete destruction" of North Korea, praised Kim in the United Nations for his courage to disarm, but added that they had much work ahead of them and that sanctions had to remain in force until North Korea was denuclearised.
Trump said Wednesday that there is no time frame for denuclearisation and added, "It doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia have voiced a view that the UN Security Council should be rewarded with Pyongyang for the measures taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: "The implementation of Security Council sanctions must be strictly continued until complete, final and verified deuklearisation occurs."
The Security Council unanimously imposed sanctions for North Korea in 2006 in an attempt to halt funding for a nuclear and ballistic programme in Pyongyang.
Pompeo met with Rio at the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second meeting.
Pompeo visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July and said progress was made, but after a few hours, North Korea called him out for "gangster demands".
North Korea has agreed to meet with Moon this month to dismantle the missile site and the nuclear complex that will be achieved if the United States takes "the appropriate measures".
He added that Kim revealed to him that these "suitable measures" refer to the security guarantees that Trump promised in Singapore and certain steps towards stabilising relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course in learning how to get a good rest
A new course at Harvard University allowed all students to get a good night’s sleep in an attempt to combat an increasingly widespread learning culture with caffeine and sleepless nights.
The academic found that students at the world's best university often have no idea about the basics of self - care.
Charles Czeisler, professor of the science of sleeping at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham Hospital and Women's Hospital, has devised a course he believes to be the first of its kind in the United States.
The idea of the course came after giving a speech about the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end of the lecture, a girl came up to me and said, "Why did I find this out only now, at the last year of college?"
She said no one told her how important the dream was, which surprised me," He told The Telegraph.
The first course this year explains to students how good sleeping habits help in academic and sports success and generally improve health.
A professor of psychiatry at Harvard School of Medicine and the head of health services at Paul Barreira University says the University decided to introduce a course after serious sleep deprivation was observed during the week.
The one-hour course consists of a series of interactive tasks.
One of these tasks includes a picture of a student dorm where students have to click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to find out what the effects of caffeine and light are, how the lack of sleep affects success and how important the sleeping routine is.
During the lecture, students also learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
After that, there is a map of the campus with interactive icons that encourage students to think about their daily routine.
"We know that student behavior will not change immediately.
But we think they have the right to know, just as you have the right to know how cigarettes affect health," Professor Czeisler added.
A culture of pride on all-night learning before exams continues to exist, says the professor and adds that modern technology and increasing pressure on students prove that sleep deprivation is an increasing problem.
The professor says that the secret weapon of students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety should be a good and quality sleep. Sleep also helps to fight weight gain because sleep deprivation affects the brain, instills it into a state of hunger and causes constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemistry and biology student from California, helped Professor Czeisler design a course after attending his first year of Harvard.
He says the course opened his eyes and inspired him to expand the course to the entire campus.
As the next step, he plans to ask all graduates to complete a similar study item before joining a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends students to turn on the alarm during sleep, as well as during waking up. They must be aware of the harmful effects of the blue light that broadcast electronic devices screens, as well as LED lights that can disrupt the circadian rhythm and cause problems with sleep.
