Almanac: Inventor of Geiger counter
And now here is the page from our Almanac in "Sunday Morning": September 30, 1882, 136 years ago and a few days ago ...the day of the birth of future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger in Germany.
Geiger developed a method of detecting and measuring radioactivity, and from this invention later developed a device known as the Geiger counter.
The main stronghold of science from that time, Geiger's counter became the main stronghold of pop culture, for example in the 1950 movie "Bells of Colorado" in which seemingly amazing scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans played the role:
Man: "What on earth is that?"
Rogers: “It is a Geiger counter, used to detect radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put these headphones on, you can actually hear atoms reacting to the radioactivity in minerals."
Evans: "Look at that, you can hear it!"
Hans Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name still lives.
