The National Foundation listens to the secret life of bats
New research carried out on the estate in Scotland’s highlands aims to discover how bats use the landscape to hunt for food.
There is hope that the results will clarify the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study carried out by scientists at the National Foundation for Scotland (NTS) will follow ordinary and swampy dwarf bats, as well as brown long-lived and river bats in Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to monitor bat activity throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile examinations using hand detectors.
Expert analysis of sound of all images will determine the frequency of bat voting and what kind it does.
Then a map of the habitat and the report will be drawn up to create a detailed picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a consultant for the protection of the nature of NTS, hopes that the results will reveal what habitat areas are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of working on the management of habitats, such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the United Kingdom have decreased significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and construction that affect shelters and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose danger, as well as fliestraps and certain chemical treatments of building materials, and pet cats attacks.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echolocation techniques to find bugs and obstacles on their flight path.
NTS, responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 acres of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
There are ten trained experts, who regularly conduct research, shelter inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization even set up the first and only bat reserve in Scotland at the Threava estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight out of ten bats inhabit Scotland.
The manager, David Thompson, says the estate is the perfect area for them.
"Here in Three we have a huge space for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all good habitats.
However, there is still much we do not know about bats, so the work we do here and at other facilities will help us to understand better what they need for progress."
It emphasizes the importance of checking the presence of bats before starting maintenance works within buildings, since unintentional destruction of one litter can kill up to 400 females and youths, thus probably destroying the entire local population.
Bats are protected and are illegal to kill, torture, or harass, or destroy their shelters.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a representative for the Scottish Bat Protection Association, encouraged the public to help.
She said: "We still have much to learn about our bats and for many of our species we simply don't know how their population is progressing."
